<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-468-208  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 468 208.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  July 31 1989 v11 n31 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-performance Novell Netware limited by bottlenecks of AT bus.andO;(Novell Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stephens, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Novell Inc says that the AT-bus architecture used on most fileservers limits local-area network performance because of busbottlenecks.andP;  The company, responding to reports that its NetWareLAN software may no longer have a performance advantage overcompeting products, conducted its own series of benchmark testswhich showed that the bus becomes saturated under heavy networktraffic.andP;  Adding more than two network adapter cards fails toincrease throughput, indicating that speed tests are revealing thelimitations of the AT bus rather than the speed of the software.andO;The company says that machines using 32-bit Extended IndustryStandard Architecture or Micro Channel Architecture buses will bemore able to utilize the extra performance of its NetWare 386 butthat NetWare 286 is currently a better buy for many users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Novell Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    NOVL.andO;Product:   NetWare 2.15 (Network operating system) (testing)NetWare 3.0 (Network operating system) (testing).andO;Topic:     Computer DesignNetwork Management SoftwareBusesLimitationsPerformanceLocal Area Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Netware 3.0 comparisons. (graph)Netware 2.12 vs. 3.0. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>